\pard\f0\fs28    {\b 16. B. barrelieri} (L.) Janka, {\i Term. Fuz.}{\b  6}: 179 (1882) ({\i B. laevigata} Lag., {\i B. sabularia} Brot.). Annual, rarely perennial; stems up to 50 cm. Lower leaves numerous, rosulate, very shortly petiolate, runcinate-pinnatifid, with 7-10 pairs of lanceolate, acuminate lobes, hispid, especially along the thick, white mid-vein, and ciliate. Cauline leaves few, sessile, more or less entire, glabrous. Sepals erect, sparsely hispid or glabrous; petals 7-12 mm, obovate, yellow with livid veins, or whitish. Siliqua 25-60 × 1·5-2·5 mm, constricted at intervals, very shortly stipitate, attenuate into a 0- to 2-seeded beak 5-30 mm long.{\i  Sandy soils. S.W. Europe.} Bl Hs Lu.
